ANS( Compute("$eqn")->cmp() );

#ANS( fun_cmp($eqn,vars=>'x') );

if ($m == 0) {$reason = "This function resembles a cosine curve in that it attains its maximum when \( x = 0 \)."}
else {$reason = "This function resembles a sine curve in that the graph is at its midline when \( x = 0 \)."};

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 

$reason  We know that the smallest value it attains is \( $actual_min \), that its midline is \( y = 0 \), so its amplitude is \( $a\).  Thus in the equation  \( f(x) = $generic[$m] \) we know that  \( A = $a \) and \(  k = 0 \). Since the graph has a period of \( \frac{\pi}{$q} \), the value for \( B = \frac{2 \pi}{\mbox{period}} = \frac{2 \pi}{\pi/$q} = 2 \cdot $q = $b \).  Finally we have a formula:
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( f(x) =  $show_eq \)

END_SOLUTION
      

